<section xml:id="sect-rational-interp">
  <title>Rational Interpolation and Approximation</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      We now extend some of the ideas above to that using rational functions instead of polynomials.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <subsection>
    <title>Padé Approximations</title>

    <p>
      The first Rational Approximation to a function that we will discuss is that of the Padé approximation.
      This is the equivalent of the Taylor Series to rational functions.
    </p>

    <p>
      Recall that a Taylor approximation to a function <m>f(x)</m> is a polynomial <m>P(x)</m> such that
      <me>
        \begin{aligned}f^{(i)}(x_{0})\amp = P^{(i)}(x_{0}) \qquad \text{for some $x_{0}$ and $i=0,1, \ldots, n$}\end{aligned}
      </me>
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The Taylor Polynomial <m>P_{2}(x)</m> to <m>f(x)=e^{-x}</m> at <m>x_{0}=0</m> is
          <me>
            \begin{aligned}P_{2}(x)\amp = 1 - x + \frac{x^{2}}{2}\end{aligned}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      In a similar manner, let
      <me>
        \begin{aligned}R_{m,n}(x)\amp = \frac{\sum_{i=0}^{m} a_{i} x^{i}}{\sum_{i=0}^{n} b_{i} x_{i}}\end{aligned}
      </me>
      where generally <m>b_{0}=1</m>.
      The Padé approximation <m>R_{m,n}(x)</m> is the rational function that satisfies:
      <me>
        \begin{aligned}f^{(i)}(x_{0})\amp = R^{(i)}_{m,n}(x)\end{aligned}
      </me>
      for <m>i=0,1,2, \ldots m+n</m>.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the Padé approximation, <m>R_{1,1}(x)</m> to <m>f(x)=e^{-x}</m> at <m>x_{0}=0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The function <m>R_{1,1}(x)</m> can be written:
          <me>
            \begin{aligned}R_{1,1}(x)\amp = \frac{a_{0} + a_{1} x}{1+b_{1}x}\end{aligned}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          To find the Padé approximation, we will need the first two derivatives of this or:
          <me>
            \begin{aligned}R_{1,1}'(x)\amp = \frac{a_{1}-a_{0}b_{1}}{(1+b_{1}x)^{2}}\\ R_{1,1}''(x)\amp = 2\frac{a_{0}b_{1}^{2}-a_{1}b_{1}}{(1+b_{1}x)^{3}}\end{aligned}
          </me>
          and then to find the coefficients <m>a_{0}, a_{1}, b_{1}</m>, these must satisfy:
          <me>
            \begin{aligned}f(0)\amp = R_{1,1}(0)\amp 1\amp = a_{0} \\ f'(0)\amp = R'_{1,1}(0)\amp -1\amp = a_{1}-a_{0}b_{1} \\ f''(0)\amp = R''_{1,1}(0)\amp 1\amp = 2(a_{0}b_{1}^{2}-a_{1}b_{1}) \\\end{aligned}
          </me>
          and using <m>a_{0}=1</m> in the second equation, one can find <m>a_{1} = -1+b_{1}</m>.
          Substituting into the 3rd equation above:
          <me>
            \begin{aligned}1\amp = 2(b_{1}^{2} - (-1+b_{1})b_{1} = 2b_{1}\end{aligned}
          </me>
          so
          <me>
            \begin{aligned}a_{0}\amp = 1\amp a_{1}\amp =- \frac{1}{2}\amp b_{1}\amp = \frac{1}{2}\end{aligned}
          </me>
          so
          <me>
            \begin{aligned}R_{1,1}(x)\amp = \frac{1-x/2}{1+x/2}= \frac{2-x}{2+x}\end{aligned}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          A plot of <m>f(x)=e^{-x}</m> and <m>R_{1,1}(x)</m> is
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-plot-1234891p">
          <caption></caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
      <![CDATA[
      \begin{tikzpicture}[yscale=0.5,xscale=2]
\draw[->] (-1.5,0) -- (1.5,0) node [above right] {$x$}; \foreach \x in {-1,1} \draw (\x,0.1) -- (\x,-0.1) node [below] {\x};
 \draw[->] (0,-0.5) -- (0,3.5) node [above right] {$y$};
\foreach \y in {1,2,3} \draw (0.1,\y) -- (-0.1,\y) node [left] {\y};
\draw[<->] plot [domain=-1.1:1.1] (\x,{exp(-\x)});
\draw[<->,dashed] plot[domain=-1.1:1.1] (\x,{(\x*(1-exp(1))+exp(1)+1)/(\x*(exp(1)-1)+exp(1)+1)});
\end{tikzpicture}
      ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      And similar to Taylor Series, increasing <m>n</m> will in general decrease the error in the approximation.
      Also similar to Taylor Series, the approximate is most accurate near the “center” (in this case, <m>x=0</m>) and the error typically increases as the distance from this center increases.
    </p>

    <p>
      Note also that since this is a rational function, there may be places where it is undefined.
      In this case, <m>x=-2</m> is a vertical asymptote of the rational function, but not the original function <m>y=e^{-x}</m>.
    </p>
  </subsection>


  <subsection>
    <title>A Hermite-Type Rational Approximation</title>

    <p>
      Lastly, we chose a rational function <m>R_{m,n}(x)</m> that matches both the derivative and function values at interpolated points.
      We will explore this through an example.
      Consider <m>f(x)=e^{-x}</m> and

    <me>
      \begin{aligned}R_{4,3}(x)\amp = \frac{a_{0}+a_{1} x + a_{2} x^{2} + a_{3} x^{3}+a_{4} x^{4}}{1 + b_{1} x + b_{2} x^{2}+ b_{3} x^{3}}\end{aligned}
    </me>


      and we wish to evaluate <m>R_{4,3}(x)</m> and its derivative at 4 points.
      Although equally-spaced points can be used, we will use the roots of <m>T_{4}(x)</m>, the Chebyshev polynomial.
      Thus we will take <m>x_{0} = -0.9238795325</m>, <m>x_{1}= -0.3826834325</m>, <m>x_{2}=0.3826834325</m>, and <m>x_{3}=0.9238795325</m>.
      We will solve:

    <me>
      \begin{aligned}R_{4,3}(x_{i})\amp = f(x_{i})\amp R'_{4,3}(x)\amp = f'(x_{i})\end{aligned}
    </me>


      and solve for the <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> values.
      Again, this is not easy to do by hand, but using a CAS, it is reasonably easy.
      The results are:

    <me>
      \begin{aligned}R_{4,3}(x)\amp = \frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}\end{aligned}
    </me>


      where

    <me>
      \begin{aligned}P(x)\amp = 1.000000011- 0.5718840492\,x+ 0.1430276148\,{x}^{2}\\\amp - 0.01904667174\,{x}^{3}+ 0.001181046601\,{x}^{4}\\ Q(x)\amp = 1+ 0.4281159555\,x+ 0.07114374318\,{x}^{2}+ 0.004705683520\,{x}^{3}\end{aligned}
    </me>
  </p>

    <p>
      A plot of the error <m>|R(x)-e^{-x}|</m> shows that this is quite accurate
    </p>

    <p>
      <em>NEED PLOT</em>
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>